<subSubSection id="4FF0F1E8FF8DFFC7A7ADF895FAB1DBE9" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="0755A263FF8DFFC7A7ADF895FEB8DB95" blockId="20.[189,382,1914,1940]" box="[189,382,1914,1940]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<heading id="5C1D150FFF8DFFC7A7ADF895FEB8DB95" bold="true" box="[189,382,1914,1940]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" reason="3">
<emphasis id="359E7E71FF8DFFC7A7ADF895FEB8DB95" bold="true" box="[189,382,1914,1940]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Natural history</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0755A263FF8DFFC7A7ADF845FAB1DBE9" blockId="20.[189,1399,1962,2025]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
Specimens live under rocks in wet, densely forested ravines, and can be found near termite mounds or ant nests. One individual was observed under the same rock as a juvenile 
<taxonomicName id="C0EAD9E0FF8DFFC7A30AF821FAB4DBE9" authority="Thorell, 1889" authorityName="Thorell" authorityYear="1889" box="[1050,1394,1998,2024]" class="Arachnida" family="Phrynidae" genus="Phrynus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amblypygi" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="goesii">
<emphasis id="359E7E71FF8DFFC7A30AF821FB0FDBE9" box="[1050,1225,1998,2024]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Phrynus goesii</emphasis>
Thorell, 1889
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="4FF0F1E8FF8CFFC6A7ADFEE6FB04DDB6" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="0755A263FF8CFFC6A7ADFEE6FEE9DD22" blockId="21.[189,303,265,291]" box="[189,303,265,291]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<heading id="5C1D150FFF8CFFC6A7ADFEE6FEE9DD22" bold="true" box="[189,303,265,291]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" reason="3">
<emphasis id="359E7E71FF8CFFC6A7ADFEE6FEE9DD22" bold="true" box="[189,303,265,291]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0755A263FF8CFFC6A7ADFED9FB04DDB6" blockId="21.[188,1399,310,439]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<bibRefCitation id="637BDF92FF8CFFC6A7ADFED9FE1EDD51" author="Teruel R. &amp; Questel K." box="[189,472,310,336]" firstAuthor="Teruel" journalOrPublisher="Boletin de la Sociedad Entomologica Aragonesa" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="15 - 18" part="49" refId="ref154490" refString="Teruel R. &amp; Questel K. 2011. A new species of Charinus Simon 1892 (Amblypygi: Charinidae) from the Leeward Islands, Lesser Antilles. Boletin de la Sociedad Entomologica Aragonesa 49: 15 - 18." title="A new species of Charinus Simon 1892 (Amblypygi: Charinidae) from the Leeward Islands, Lesser Antilles" type="journal article" year="2011">Teruel &amp; Questel (2011)</bibRefCitation>
mentioned the presence of secondary sexual dimorphism in 
<taxonomicName id="C0EAD9E0FF8CFFC6A384FED9FACDDD51" authorityName="Teruel &amp; Questel" authorityYear="2011" box="[1172,1291,310,336]" class="Arachnida" family="Charinidae" genus="Charinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amblypygi" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bruneti">
<emphasis id="359E7E71FF8CFFC6A384FED9FACDDD51" box="[1172,1291,310,336]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">C. bruneti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in which the carapace and genital operculum are proportionally narrower in males than in females. This would be unique among amblypygids and a larger number of specimens should be analysed and measured to test this hypothesis, as 
<bibRefCitation id="637BDF92FF8CFFC6A68AFE73FD7EDDB6" author="Teruel R. &amp; Questel K." box="[410,696,412,439]" firstAuthor="Teruel" journalOrPublisher="Boletin de la Sociedad Entomologica Aragonesa" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="15 - 18" part="49" refId="ref154490" refString="Teruel R. &amp; Questel K. 2011. A new species of Charinus Simon 1892 (Amblypygi: Charinidae) from the Leeward Islands, Lesser Antilles. Boletin de la Sociedad Entomologica Aragonesa 49: 15 - 18." title="A new species of Charinus Simon 1892 (Amblypygi: Charinidae) from the Leeward Islands, Lesser Antilles" type="journal article" year="2011">Teruel &amp; Questel (2011)</bibRefCitation>
only measured two individuals of each sex..
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
